<h2>The question</h2>
<p>
  Decision <a href="/backlog/1963-composition-rubric-re-judged-to-framework-parity-strict-per-/">#1963</a> sets a
  strict per-case composition-mechanism rubric for Web Everything, judged against a <strong>framework-parity,
  zero-compromise bar</strong>: ergonomics ≥ React/Vue/Svelte/Solid, zero layout/CSS/a11y compromise, a solution
  for every case, open to net-new mechanisms, and clean in plain HTML <em>and</em> JSX. This survey benchmarks
  each case against the leading frameworks and against the FUI tree, and asks the hard question directly: can a
  native-custom-elements system match framework composition DX, and where (if anywhere) must it invent? Catalog
  companion: <a href="/research/dom-less-composition/">dom-less-composition</a>.
</p>

<h2>The spine — the host node is the API surface, so it is a budgeted resource</h2>
<p>
  A framework component is a <strong>function/object</strong> in a virtual tree or compiled output; only leaf
  elements reify as DOM, so ten nested providers cost <strong>zero</strong> DOM nodes. A custom element is
  <strong>defined as a DOM element</strong> — <code>customElements.define</code> binds behaviour to a <em>tag</em>,
  and a tag is a node with a layout box, an event-path position, an accessibility entry, and a <code>:host</code>.
  Slotting, Shadow-DOM scoping, <code>connectedCallback</code> lifecycle, <code>ElementInternals</code> semantics,
  and focus are <strong>all keyed off that node</strong> — you cannot have them and not have the node.
</p>
<p>
  So the platform charges per node <em>for a reason</em>, and no emerging standard removes it. The correct
  response is not to wait for a primitive but to <strong>budget the host node</strong>: pay it only where you need
  slot / shadow / AX-identity / lifecycle; for everything else use a <strong>zero-node mechanism</strong>. That is
  exactly what frameworks do — they compile structural layers away into functions/directives. <strong>Framework
  parity for WE is a discipline, not a missing feature.</strong>
</p>

