<h2>The contested case — deep structural composition</h2>
<p>
  No shipping or proposed standard makes a <em>registered</em> custom element cost zero nodes — they reduce
  per-node <em>cost</em>, not node <em>count</em>: <code>display:contents</code> removes the box (AX regression
  fixed Safari&nbsp;16 / Firefox&nbsp;62; can't be a focusable host); <code>subgrid</code> aligns through a
  wrapper; <code>Node.moveBefore()</code> (Chrome&nbsp;133) makes reparenting non-destructive; <strong>DOM Parts
  <code>ChildNodePart</code></strong> is proposal-stage (since 2017, unshipped) and targets <em>content</em>
  regions, not CE hosts. The pattern that reaches zero-node parity — Haunted <code>virtual()</code>, Lit
  directives, Stencil functional components — does so by <strong>abandoning the registered host</strong>.
</p>
<p>
  Two honest readings survive, and #1963 forks on them: (a) <strong>discipline</strong> — parity is achievable
  today by routing structural layers through zero-node function/directive render (WE has JSX functional components
  and comment-anchor directives), reserving registered hosts for slot/shadow/AX/lifecycle; (b) <strong>invent</strong>
  — HTML-declarative true-zero-node deep nesting still wants a primitive (or a generalized transient-to-comments
  bridge), since plain HTML has only elements, not functions. DOM Parts is the standards-track watch item, not a
  blocker.
</p>

